# Navigation & Routing Standards

These rules govern all files in `src/navigation/`. React Navigation v7 is the sole routing library.

## Param List Typing

Every navigator must be created with an explicit generic param list type. All param lists must be defined in `src/navigation/types.ts`.

- Declare separate param lists per navigator: `RootStackParamList`, `AuthStackParamList`, `AppTabParamList`.
- Use `undefined` for screens that accept no params — do not use `{}` or omit the key.
- Augment `ReactNavigation.RootParamList` globally so `useNavigation()` is typed at the root level.
- Export typed screen prop helpers: `RootStackScreenProps`, `AuthStackScreenProps`, `AppTabScreenProps`.

```typescript
// BAD — untyped navigator, params inferred as any
const Stack = createNativeStackNavigator();

// BAD — param list defined inline in the navigator file
type LocalParams = { Home: { user: User } };
const Stack = createNativeStackNavigator<LocalParams>();

// GOOD — centralized types in src/navigation/types.ts
export type RootStackParamList = {
  Auth: undefined;
  App: undefined;
  Modal: { modalType: ModalType };
};

export type AuthStackParamList = {
  Login: undefined;
  Register: undefined;
  OTP: { phoneNumber: string };
};

// GOOD — typed navigator factory
const Stack = createNativeStackNavigator<AuthStackParamList>();
```

Screens outside this directory must consume typed props:

```typescript
import type { AppTabScreenProps } from "@/navigation/types";

type Props = AppTabScreenProps<"Feed">;

const FeedScreen = (_props: Props): React.JSX.Element => {
  // ...
};
```

## Auth / App Flow Isolation

Authentication and authenticated application flows must remain **totally isolated**.

- `AuthNavigator` owns only auth screens (`Login`, `Register`, `OTP`).
- `AppNavigator` owns only post-auth screens (tab stacks: `Feed`, `Booking`, `Journey`, `Settings`).
- `RootNavigator` gates between `Auth` and `App` stacks — never mix auth screens into the tab navigator or app screens into the auth stack.
- Do not conditionally render individual auth screens inside `AppNavigator` or vice versa.

```typescript
// BAD — auth screen registered inside the app tab navigator
<Tab.Screen name="Login" component={LoginScreen} />

// BAD — business screen inside auth stack
<Stack.Screen name="Feed" component={FeedScreen} />

// GOOD — root-level gate, separate navigators
<Stack.Navigator screenOptions={{ headerShown: false }}>
  {isAuthenticated ? (
    <Stack.Screen name="App" component={AppNavigator} />
  ) : (
    <Stack.Screen name="Auth" component={AuthNavigator} />
  )}
</Stack.Navigator>
```

## Navigation Params — Minimal Payloads

Navigation params are for **routing context only**, not data transport.

- Params must be JSON-serializable: strings, numbers, booleans, enums, and small record IDs.
- Do not pass full domain entities, arrays of objects, nested graphs, or callback functions through `navigation.navigate`.
- For complex or shared data, read from Zustand stores or fetch by ID in the destination screen via a service call.
- Keep param interfaces narrow — prefer a single ID field over duplicating entity shape.

```typescript
// BAD — dumps entire entity through navigation
navigation.navigate("Booking", {
  booking: {
    id: "bk_123",
    salon: { id: "s_1", name: "Studio", services: [...] },
    stylist: { /* ... */ },
  },
});

// BAD — non-serializable callback
navigation.navigate("Modal", { onConfirm: () => submitForm() });

// GOOD — pass a record ID, resolve data at destination
navigation.navigate("Booking", { bookingId: "bk_123" });

// In BookingScreen:
const { bookingId } = route.params;
const booking = useBooking(bookingId); // hook fetches from store or API
```

Param list definitions must reflect this constraint:

```typescript
// BAD
export type AppTabParamList = {
  Booking: { booking: BookingEntity };
};

// GOOD
export type AppTabParamList = {
  Feed: undefined;
  Booking: { bookingId: string } | undefined;
  Journey: undefined;
  Settings: undefined;
};
```

## Navigator File Conventions

- One navigator per file: `RootNavigator.tsx`, `AuthNavigator.tsx`, `AppNavigator.tsx`.
- Navigators must not contain business logic, API calls, or Zustand mutations — only routing structure and screen registration.
- Use `screenOptions` at the navigator level for shared config; override per-screen only when necessary.
- Placeholder screen shells are acceptable during scaffolding but must be replaced with typed screen imports from `src/screens/`.

## Type-Safe Navigation Calls

Use typed navigation hooks — never cast navigation objects.

```typescript
// BAD
(navigation as any).navigate("OTP", { phone: number });

// GOOD
import type { NativeStackNavigationProp } from "@react-navigation/native-stack";
import type { AuthStackParamList } from "@/navigation/types";

type AuthNavigation = NativeStackNavigationProp<AuthStackParamList>;

const handleSubmit = (navigation: AuthNavigation, phoneNumber: string): void => {
  navigation.navigate("OTP", { phoneNumber });
};
```
